about: Hey! Im Daniel, Im a software developer who loves to travel. I come from Seattle USA but have been living in Stockholm for 5 years. Check out my globati page. I hope you enjoy Stockholm, send me an email if you have any questions!
display: You can email me at daniel@globati.com if you have any questions. :)

recommendations.description: If you want to see an awesome ship from the vasa era which looks like it is straight out of pirates of the carribean, then look no further. The Vasa ship is one of the best preserved old boats in the world, and is truly amazing. This one is highly recommended by me.
recommendations.title: Vasa museum

recommendations.description: The best pizza in Stockholm! Omnipollo uses woodfire pizza ovens to make traditional neapolitan pizza. It is amazing!... And for dessert try the chocolate stout beer. :)
recommendations.title: Omnipollo

recommendations.description: Really tasty Tex Mex food, great drinks, live music on the weekends and sits in the oldest old town in Europe.
recommendations.title: Geronimos

recommendations.description: Hands down the best tacos in Stockholm. Not only that but it is the only place in Scandinavia that hand makes their tortillas daily. Come here!
recommendations.title: La Neta

recommendations.description: Go have drinks at mossbacke. This Swedish summertime favorite is a hot spot for locals who want to have an after work drink (AW) and those who are looking for a party. It is even mentioned in classic Swedish literature.
recommendations.title: Mossebacke

recommendations.description: With your pals and just wanna go out and play some sweet games? At Ugglan you can play the classic Swedish game boule, play pingis (ping pong), pool, video games, and more. There is also great beer and is in the cool hipster area called Södermalm. Kör på!
recommendations.title: Ugglan (Game bar)

recommendations.description: Surfers is in a cozy part of town, and cook up some of the best Chinese food in town. I highly recommend coming here if you are looking for something a little out of the ordinary.
recommendations.title: Surfers

recommendations.description:
This is an awesome brewery tour with great beer... You can get their normal stuff att Systembolaget but if you  want to try their good stuff that isn't available in stores then check out their brew tour..... see 
their website for more info.....http://sigtunabrygghus.se/
recommendations.title: Sigtuna brewery tour

recommendations.description: Here is a lot of restaurants close to the hostel where I used to work. In particular they have a nice place downstairs that serves open faced sandwiches and good beer. And on the street level there is a restaurant called pyttyrian which serves traditional scandinavian food. It does not have the greatest ambience because it is located in sort of a mall type place....But it is close by and its cheap.
recommendations.title: Kungshallen

recommendations.description:
Stockholms burgeoning craft beer movement is best experienced, in my view, from a stool at Omnipollos Hatt. Modern Swedish beer culture draws influence from the US, UK, Belgium and Germany and all are on show at Omnipollo.

The simple yet detailed interior creates a relaxed atmosphere,  blending hanging gardens, with psychedelic patterning and some of the best wall tiles I've ever seen. Music tends to stick towards hip hop but may differ depending on whose pouring.

Did I mention they have a Neapolitan pizza oven? No. 2 if you need your mind made up for you..
recommendations.title: Pizza and beer that's so good that you'll forget the 'before' shot

recommendations.description: Many people flock to the viewing platform above Gondolen but my money is walking either East or West for less interrupted views. Katerinavägen takes a light incline that leads you to wonderful views over Slussen, Gamla Stan, Skeppsholmen and Djurgården. Continue along Fjällgatan (where Katarinavägen starts to turn south into Söder) for a kiosk to enjoy an ice cream with your view.
recommendations.title: Katarinavägen

recommendations.description: Simply one of the best spots in the city, an esplanade along the shore of Lake Mälaren. I used to ride Norr Mälarstrand every day, to and from work, and it was the perfect reminder of why I live in Stockholm. Continue along to Rålambshovsparken for BBQs, beach volleyball and boule in the summer or slip back into the streets of Kungsholmen for lunch and dinner.
recommendations.title: Norr Mälarstrand

recommendations.description: Central Stockholm consists of 14 islands and you'll find yourself crossing bridges every now and again as you navigate the city. One of my favourite activities during summer is to hire a kayak hit the water. Circumnavigating Kungsholmen will reveal sunbathing Swedes on the rocks at Kristineberg before rounding into Riddarfjärden where you will pass Långholmen. Go to the far side here into the canal between Långholmen and Södermalm for a little inner city oasis where polished, wooden boats wait patiently for their owners. Head towards Gamla Stan for views of Riddarholmen, Slussen, Södermalm and City Hall before taking the canal between Kungsholmen and Norrmalm. If you have the whole day, consider heading west towards Drottningholm Palace.
recommendations.title: Water views by your own hand

recommendations.description: You're in Stockholm, it's Tuesday and it's lunch time. The taco gods are demanding a sacrifice. Fear not, La Neta has you covered. I usually grab a Taco (pirata) and quesadilla (chorizo) but pick your fancy as it's hard to go wrong. If you're on a budget then skip the Modelo Negra as your bill will almost double. There are a couple of these in Stockholm but I always go to the spot on Upplandsgatan. Don'y forget to load up on fresh salsas after picking up your order. On weekdays that do a lunch special from 11-14.
recommendations.title: Travelling but Taco Tuesday is life

recommendations.description: Ivar Los Park is firmly the latter. Located in Södermalm the park is situated just behind the very popular Monteliusvägen - a walking path with a similar, close to identical view - but for some reason it comes in at second place for me. The rear of the park has some of the coolest cubby houses in Stockholm so be careful if you use the rear entrance as kids will running and screaming in every which direction. Fear not though, as you come to the front of the park a lazy calmness fills the air. Strictly speaking you aren't allowed alcohol here (think of the kids!) but a few beers in moderation should be fine. If you'd like more space for a BBQ and volleyball or football head to Rålambshovsparken.
recommendations.title: There are views and then there are views

recommendations.description: Stockholm is undeniably beautiful, but if you need to be convinced or perhaps just need a reminder go for a walk along Karlavägen. Running through the bougie area of Östermalm, most tourists will visit Karlaplan (literally just a roundabout in winter, but quite a lovely fountain and shaded area in summer) and not really bother walking down the length of Karlavägen. I urge you to. It's nice.. like, really nice.
recommendations.title: Fancy a mid-town promenade?

recommendations.description: While I'm not too fond of theme parks, Gröna Lund's extensive concert line up during summer is nothing to be scoffed at. Drawing acts that included Elton John this year - personally I went to Slayer, Alice Cooper and Megadeth and plan to go to see Patti Smith when she performs - there is pretty much something for everyone. It's also great value. Season entrance tickets are 250 SEK, which is generally a lower fee to see any one of these acts alone. The park does have a maximum capacity, which was reached when Elton John performed. Depending on the artist and your preferred location to the stage you may have to go minutes to hours ahead of the start time to be guaranteed a spot in the crowd. Just use common sense though, the bigger the star the earlier you should arrive.
recommendations.title: World class concerts

recommendations.description: So, just about every big city is or has been going through an American burger renaissance and Stockholm is no different. If you want a sure thing then head to Lily’s Burger. There are two locations but I’ve only been to the one in Södermalm. What sets Lily’s apart for me is their no nonsense offerings and value. You won’t find a basic bread and meat burger for 100 SEK. The sweet potato fries are also the best I’ve had. If the urge for a burger hits then check it out.
recommendations.title: Need to hit a burger?

recommendations.description: Söder Mälastrand is a great place to stretch your legs, either if you need a casual walk or a more intense jog. Beginning from Slussen head west towards Långholmen. This side of Mäalaren catches the sunset and has a nice view to Riddarholmen and Kungsholmen, where you have the city hall. If you prefer a longer route then continue into Långholmen or across Västerbron into Kungsholmen where you will find Rålambshovsparken.
recommendations.title: Autumn walks on Söder Mälarstrand

about: I'm a Stockholm local, having lived here for 3 years. More interested in fancy places, as well as underground music.

recommendations.description: A lovely out-of-the-way-but-worth-it cafe. Open year round, serves locally grown, freshly cooked deliciousness.
recommendations.title: Kanaans Trädgårdscafé

recommendations.description: An awesome chain of hip bakeries serving up traditional Swedish pastries. The Wallonbulle (or “Walloon bun”) is a must-try!
recommendations.title: Fabrique

recommendations.description: Michelin stars abound in Mathias Dahlgren's vegetarian-only Rutabaga. Amazing good, great service, a little bit on the pricier end (but worth it)
recommendations.title: Rutabaga

recommendations.description: Avant-garde theatre underneath a bridge. Experimental works, mostly in the Swedish language, and a very unique stage setup add to a unique experience.
recommendations.title: Teatern Under Brön

recommendations.description: Stockholm's latest techno and house club, focusing on up-and-coming DJs. Free entrance, opens at 3PM and closes at 3AM.
recommendations.title: mmmmm

recommendations.description: The closest you will get to a raw, intense Berlin-style techno experience in Stockholm. Major emphasis on techno, minimal, and house. Sometimes there's a cover. This is a hard party without pretension. In the summers they got a rooftop.
recommendations.title: Slakthuset

about: City Backpackers is the base camp for the Stockholm explorer. If you like meeting new people, you'll have the time of your life here. We love showing Stockholm to our guests. All year we arrange tours and adventures, such as guided bike rides and Kayak tours in the summer and our awesome Viking Sauna Tour in winter.

recommendations.description: Nybergs Hembageri & Konditori is a great place to enter the Swedish world of fika. With interiors made to look and feel like a living room, Swedish patisseries are a wonderful place to refuel during your inner city exploration. Seasonal pastries include semla in February and lussebullar in December. Did we mention it's on the same street as the hostel?
recommendations.title: A classic Swedish patisserie

recommendations.description: If you're into a more relaxed clubbing vibe then Trädgården / Underbron is your little ray of Berlin in Stockholm. You will find a comprehensive cross-section of our city's hipster and alternate identifiers. Genres can vary drastically here so we suggest checking their website before visiting. Expect a modest  cover (or free entry) early in the evening and a exorbitant one during peak hours, after midnight.
recommendations.title: A bit of Berlin in Stockholm

recommendations.description: The Stockholm culture center hosts many initiatives every year, with dozens of contemporary cultural events, including photo exhibitions, art executions, concerts, films, debates. Many of the exhibitions are free or have free days (Monday). Take the escalator or lift to the top floor for a view across Stockholm's inner city and the iconic black and white triangles of plattan.
recommendations.title: Stockholm's Kulturhuset

recommendations.description: If craft beer is on your radar then Omnipollos hatt should be too. Showcasing some of the best beers in Sweden, the menu also includes great nordic region and collaboration beers with breweries in the UK and US. Add in a tap takeover every so often and you've got a great rotating menu. Be sure to try the pizza too!
recommendations.title: Omnipollos hatt

recommendations.description: If you're into new-old or mostly old-old Nordic design then Myrorna is a must. If it's pre-loved clothing, interior decorations or vinyl records they will more likely than not have what you're after. It is amazingly curated too and is jam packed with bargains of a bygone era.
recommendations.title: Retro Nordic design

recommendations.description: Looking for a fast, affordable, Swedish lunch? Citykonditoriet offers just that. Take the stairs to the third level and line up for the lunch special. Usually around 80-90 SEK and includes a meal, salad and coffee. As the name suggests, they also have a long list of pastries. The interior is also very charming. A favourite amongst City Backpackers staff.
recommendations.title: Citykonditoriet

recommendations.description: Picturesque views of Stockholm's inner city are best observed by walking Norr Mälarstrand. You will get a great view of Riddarholmen, Gamla Stan, Södermalm and Långholmen. Wonderful any time of year, it is also popular among the cities running enthusiasts.
recommendations.title: Norr Mälarstrand
